Quality of service classes, guaranteed, burstable, and best effort.

Kubernetes assigns each pod a quality of service class based on its resource settings. You do not set the class directly. The ay-pee-eye server computes it. And the class matters when a node runs low on memory and has to evict something.

There are three classes. A pod is guaranteed when every container has both requests and limits set, for both see-pee-you and memory, with the request equal to the limit for each. A pod is burstable when at least one container has some request or limit, but it does not meet the strict guaranteed criteria. That is the eighty percent case. And a pod is best effort when no container has any requests or limits at all.

Why does this matter. When the kube-let detects memory pressure, it evicts pods in a specific order. Best effort pods first. Then burstable pods, prioritizing those using memory above their requests. And guaranteed pods last, only if there is literally no other choice.

So the cheapest insurance against eviction is to set the memory request equal to the memory limit. That makes the pod guaranteed, and the kube-let will not touch it under normal memory pressure.

One distinction to keep straight, because they sound similar. An out of memory kill is when a single container exceeds its own memory limit, so the kernel kills that process, and you see it in the container's last state with a raised restart count. An eviction is when the whole pod is removed by the kube-let to relieve node level pressure, even if no single container broke its own limit. Different mechanism, different blast radius.
